#*: Most food scholars agree that the '''tapas''' tradition originated in the wine-growing regions of [[Andalusia]], eventually spreading throughout the country. The Moors (Muslim Arabs), who dominated Spain from the beginning of the eighth century until the end of the fifteenth century, settled in the same area, and their meze tradition undoubtably had an influence on the rise of the '''tapa'''... Another tale attributes the birth to a decree by {{w|Alfonso X of Castile|Alfonso X}} instructing all inns to serve tidbits of food with the wine they poured to ensure against public drunkeness.

